					<div lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>Return to <a href="/wiki/index.php/Microecon:Main" title="Microecon:Main">the list of lectures</a>.
<br /><br />
<strong>The lecture notes are a collaborative effort of the participants in the course. You are not required to contribute to the lecture notes, but are encouraged to do so. Together, we can create resources that will be helpful to everyone.</strong></p>
<h1> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes_for_Week_3:_2.1._What_is_Consumer_Surplus.3F">Notes for Week 3: 2.1. What is Consumer Surplus?</span></h1>
<ul>
<li><p>Measure happiness and benefits of inhabitants in units of measure, for example, the dollar.</p></li>
<li><p>Consumer Surplus is the difference between what you are willing to pay and actual price paid.</p></li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="For_any_good.2C_your_willingness_to_pay_has_to_be_higher_than_the_price_you_pay_for_a_consumer_surplus_to_occur.">For any good, your willingness to pay has to be higher than the price you pay for a consumer surplus to occur.</span></h2>
<p><i>[Consumer Surplus]= (Willingness to pay) - (Price)</i></p>
<ul>
<li><p>If prices fall at the same WTP (willingness to pay), the consumer surplus rises.</p></li>
<li><p>If prices rise at the same WTP (willingness to pay), the consumer surplus falls.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><b>Said another way:</b></p>
<p>An increase in price, lowers consumer surplus.</p>
<p>A decrease in price, raises consumer surplus.</p>
<p></p>
<p><b>Consumer welfare</b> is the result of a change in consumer surplus.  If Consumer Surplus (CS) increases, then Consumer welfare increases, and if CS decreases, then Consumer welfare decreases.</p>

